<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-slopefield-matching" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Reading and Matching Slope Fields</title>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    In the previous page we built a slope field from scratch for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 2y</m>,
    drawing tick marks one row at a time until the full picture emerged. That is a great way
    to understand what a slope field is. But in practice, you will often be handed a slope field
    and asked to figure out which differential equation it came from, or to identify which
    picture shows the correct solution curves. That requires a different skill: reading a slope
    field strategically rather than building it from the ground up.
  </p>
  <p>
    The good news is that you do not need to check every single point. A few well-chosen
    locations, like the coordinate axes, can tell you almost everything you need to know.
    Let's build that intuition now with an example.
  </p>

  <p>
    For <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m>, the slope at any point <m>(x, y)</m> is just <m>x + y</m>.
    Let's compute a few values and draw the corresponding tick marks.
  </p>

  <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
    <row header="yes">
      <cell><m>x</m></cell>
      <cell><m>y</m></cell>
      <cell><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m></cell>
    </row>
    <row><cell><m>-1</m></cell><cell><m>-1</m></cell><cell><m>-2</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>-1</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>-1</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>-1</m></cell><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>-1</m></cell><cell><m>-1</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>1</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>-1</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>0</m></cell><cell><m>1</m></cell></row>
    <row><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell><m>2</m></cell></row>
  </tabular>



  <p>
    Now watch the full slope field build up row by row.
    For each tick, the display shows the current <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, and computed slope.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-slopefield-xy">
    <caption>
      The slope field for <m>dy/dx = x + y</m>, built row by row starting at <m>y = 0</m>.
      Notice how the ticks get steeper as you move away from the line <m>y = -x</m>,
      where the slope is zero.
    </caption>
    <interactive xml:id="interactive-slopefield-xy" iframe="interactive-slopefield-xy.html" width="100%" aspect="3:2">
      <static>
        <p>
          A slope field for <m>dy/dx = x + y</m> on the grid <m>-3 \leq x \leq 3</m>,
          <m>-3 \leq y \leq 3</m>. Each tick mark at <m>(x,y)</m> has slope <m>x+y</m>.
          Along <m>y=0</m>, ticks are flat at the origin, tilt right for positive <m>x</m>
          and left for negative <m>x</m>. Along <m>x=0</m>, ticks tilt upward for positive
          <m>y</m> and downward for negative <m>y</m>.
        </p>
      </static>
    </interactive>
  </figure>

  <!-- ==================== MC 1: match slope field ==================== -->

  <p>
    Two slope fields are shown below. Exactly one is the slope field for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m>.
    Rather than checking every point, be strategic: check what happens along the axes.
    Along <m>x = 0</m>, the slope should equal <m>y</m>,
    so ticks above the origin should tilt upward and ticks below should tilt downward.
    Does that rule out one of the fields?
  </p>

  <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" margins="0% 5%">
    <figure xml:id="fig-mc-field-A">
      <caption>Field A</caption>
      <interactive xml:id="interactive-match-A" iframe="slopefield-match-A.html" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <static>
          <p>Slope field A. Along the y-axis, ticks tilt upward above the origin and downward
          below, consistent with slope equals y when x equals 0. Ticks are steepest in the
          upper-right and lower-left corners. This is the correct slope field for dy/dx = x+y.</p>
        </static>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <figure xml:id="fig-mc-field-B">
      <caption>Field B</caption>
      <interactive xml:id="interactive-match-B" iframe="slopefield-match-B.html" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <static>
          <p>Slope field B. Along the y-axis, ticks tilt downward above the origin and upward
          below, the opposite of what dy/dx equals x plus y predicts. This is the incorrect field.</p>
        </static>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
  </sidebyside>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-mc-slopefield-match">
    <statement>
      <p>Which of the two slope fields above is the slope field for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m>?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>Field A</p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! Check the <m>x = 0</m> axis: slope <m>= y</m> there, so ticks above the origin
            tilt upward and ticks below tilt downward. Field A shows exactly this.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>Field B</p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite. Check the <m>x = 0</m> axis in Field B: the ticks above the origin tilt
            downward and the ticks below tilt upward. That is the opposite of what
            <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m> predicts, since the slope along <m>x = 0</m> should equal <m>y</m>.
            Field B is actually the slope field for <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x - y</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <!-- ==================== MC 2: solution curves ==================== -->

  <p>
    Both pictures below show the slope field for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m> with solution
    curves drawn on top. Recall: a solution curve must be <em>tangent</em> to the slope field
    at every point. It flows with the ticks, never cutting across them at a sharp angle.
  </p>

  <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" margins="0% 5%">
    <figure xml:id="fig-mc-curves-A">
      <caption>Picture A</caption>
      <interactive xml:id="interactive-curves-A" iframe="slopefield-curves-A.html" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <static>
          <p>Picture A: the slope field for dy/dx equals x plus y with correct solution curves overlaid.
          The curves flow tangentially with the tick marks, sweeping steeply upward in the upper-right
          and steeply downward in the lower-left. This is the correct picture.</p>
        </static>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
    <figure xml:id="fig-mc-curves-B">
      <caption>Picture B</caption>
      <interactive xml:id="interactive-curves-B" iframe="slopefield-curves-B.html" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
        <static>
          <p>Picture B: the slope field for dy/dx equals x plus y with incorrect solution curves overlaid.
          The curves cross the tick marks at sharp angles rather than flowing with them. This is the
          incorrect picture.</p>
        </static>
      </interactive>
    </figure>
  </sidebyside>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-mc-slopefield-curves">
    <statement>
      <p>Which of the two pictures above shows correct solution curves for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m>?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>Picture A</p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! In Picture A the curves flow tangentially with the tick marks everywhere.
            They sweep steeply upward in the upper-right where the field is steep, exactly as
            a solution to <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m> must.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>Picture B</p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not quite. The curves in Picture B cross the tick marks at sharp angles rather than
            flowing with them. A solution curve must be tangent to the field at every point.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </exercise>

  <!-- YouTube video -->
  <figure xml:id="video-slopefield-matching">
    <caption>Reading and matching slope fields (video)</caption>
    <video xml:id="yt-slopefield-matching" youtube="Lbqk61_sSBA" width="60%"/>
  </figure>

</section>
